# AI Workflow Builder - Cursor Rules

## 🎯 PROJECT CONTEXT
You are building a revolutionary AI workflow builder with drag-and-drop interface, real-time execution, natural language workflow creation, and MCP server integration. This is a Next.js 14 app with TypeScript, Supabase, and React Flow.

## 🔥 CORE PRINCIPLES
- Build with excellence and precision
- Prioritize user experience and performance
- Create scalable, maintainable code
- Follow TypeScript best practices
- Implement comprehensive error handling
- Write production-ready code

## 📋 TECHNICAL REQUIREMENTS

### Framework & Technologies
- **Frontend**: Next.js 14 with App Router, React 18, TypeScript
- **UI**: Tailwind CSS, Shadcn/UI, React Flow, Lucide Icons
- **Database**: Supabase (PostgreSQL with real-time subscriptions)
- **Authentication**: Supabase Auth
- **AI**: OpenAI GPT-4, Anthropic Claude, LangChain
- **State**: Zustand, React Query
- **Deployment**: Vercel (primary), Railway (alternative)

### File Structure Requirements
```
src/
├── app/                    # Next.js 14 App Router
├── components/
│   ├── ui/                 # Reusable UI components
│   ├── workflow/           # Workflow-specific components
│   ├── nodes/              # Node UI components
│   ├── chat/               # Chat widget components
│   └── auth/               # Authentication components
├── lib/
│   ├── supabase/           # Supabase configuration
│   ├── workflow-engine/    # Core workflow execution
│   ├── node-system/        # Node architecture
│   ├── mcp-server/         # MCP server implementation
│   └── utils/              # Utility functions
├── hooks/                  # React hooks
├── types/                  # TypeScript type definitions
└── stores/                 # Zustand state stores
```

## 🎨 CODING STANDARDS

### TypeScript Rules
- Use strict TypeScript configuration
- Define interfaces for all data structures
- Use type guards for runtime type checking
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes
- Use `const assertions` for literal types
- No `any` types - use `unknown` if necessary
- Export types from dedicated type files

### React Best Practices
- Use functional components with hooks
- Implement proper error boundaries
- Use React.memo for performance optimization
- Prefer controlled components
- Use proper key props for lists
- Implement loading and error states
- Use Suspense for code splitting

### Next.js App Router Rules
- Use server components by default
- Add 'use client' only when necessary
- Implement proper metadata for SEO
- Use proper loading.tsx and error.tsx files
- Follow App Router file conventions
- Use route groups for organization

### Component Architecture
- Create reusable UI components in `/components/ui/`
- Use composition over inheritance
- Implement proper prop interfaces
- Use forwardRef for ref forwarding
- Create compound components for complex UI
- Use render props pattern when appropriate

## 🗄️ DATABASE RULES

### Supabase Best Practices
- Use Row Level Security (RLS) for all tables
- Create proper database policies
- Use TypeScript types generated from schema
- Implement proper error handling for database operations
- Use real-time subscriptions for live updates
- Optimize queries with proper indexes

### Data Modeling
- Use UUIDs for primary keys
- Include created_at and updated_at timestamps
- Use JSONB for flexible data storage
- Implement proper foreign key constraints
- Design for scalability and performance

## 🔧 WORKFLOW ENGINE RULES

### Node System Architecture
- All nodes must extend BaseNode abstract class
- Implement proper input/output validation
- Use JSON Schema for configuration validation
- Create comprehensive error handling
- Implement proper logging and metrics
- Design for extensibility and pluggability

### Execution Engine
- Use topological sorting for node execution order
- Implement proper state management
- Create comprehensive error recovery
- Add execution monitoring and metrics
- Use event-driven architecture
- Implement proper cancellation handling

## ⚙️ COMPREHENSIVE CONFIGURATION SYSTEM RULES

### Configuration Architecture
- Implement three-tier hierarchy: Global → Workflow → Node
- Use NodeConfiguration interface for all configuration types
- Create ConfigurationManager for validation and persistence
- Implement proper configuration inheritance and overrides
- Use type-safe configuration with comprehensive TypeScript interfaces
- Support configuration versioning and migration

### Configuration UI Standards
- Create intuitive configuration panels with tabs and sections
- Implement visual prompt builder with drag-and-drop components
- Add real-time configuration testing and validation
- Use consistent parameter controls (sliders, dropdowns, text inputs)
- Implement configuration preview with live updates
- Add configuration templates and sharing capabilities

### Credential Management
- Use AES-256-GCM encryption for all sensitive data
- Implement credential hierarchy (Global → Workflow → Node)
- Add automatic credential rotation and expiration
- Create comprehensive audit logging for all credential access
- Use secure credential storage with Supabase Vault
- Implement credential testing and validation

### Variable System
- Create context-aware variable resolution
- Support dynamic variable injection from previous nodes
- Implement safe expression evaluation for variables
- Add variable type checking and validation
- Create variable management UI with real-time preview
- Support workflow-level and system-level variables

### Configuration Testing
- Implement comprehensive testing framework for all configurations
- Add real-time configuration validation
- Create performance monitoring for configuration changes
- Support test data injection and mock responses
- Add configuration debugging tools and insights
- Implement automatic configuration optimization suggestions

### Node-Specific Configuration
- Create specialized configuration UIs for each node type
- Database nodes: Visual SQL query builder with parameterized queries
- Email nodes: Template editor with variable injection
- Webhook nodes: Request builder with authentication options
- AI nodes: Advanced prompt builder with template system
- Logic nodes: Visual condition builder and data transformation tools

### Configuration Import/Export
- Support encrypted configuration export with selective data inclusion
- Implement smart configuration import with conflict resolution
- Add configuration templates for sharing and reuse
- Create configuration migration system for version updates
- Support multiple export formats (JSON, YAML, Templates)
- Implement configuration backup and restore functionality

### Environment Management
- Support multiple environments (Development, Staging, Production)
- Implement environment-specific configuration overrides
- Add environment switching with configuration comparison
- Create environment-specific credential management
- Support A/B testing for configuration variations
- Implement configuration deployment pipelines

### Advanced Configuration Features
- Add configuration versioning with rollback capabilities
- Implement configuration change tracking and history
- Create configuration analytics and usage insights
- Support configuration templates marketplace
- Add collaborative configuration editing
- Implement configuration approval workflows for teams

### Performance & Security
- Encrypt all configuration data at rest and in transit
- Implement proper caching for configuration access
- Use optimized queries for configuration retrieval
- Add rate limiting for configuration operations
- Create comprehensive security audit trails
- Implement proper access control for configuration management

